04934nam a22007095i 9780226354613DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019723479  a9780226354613  a(DE-B1597)549490  a(OCoLC)1193128127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH78 4aQH78b.S475 2021 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a576.842231 aSepkoski, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCatastrophic Thinking :bExtinction and the Value of Diversity from Darwin to the Anthropocene /cDavid Sepkoski. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b15 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ascience.culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Why Extinction Matters -- t1. The Meaning of Extinction: Catastrophe, Equilibrium, and Diversity -- t2. Extinction in a Victorian Key -- t3. Catastrophe and Modernity -- t4. Extinction in the Shadow of the Bomb -- t5. The Asteroid and the Dinosaur -- t6. A Sixth Extinction? The Making of a Biodiversity Crisis -- tEpilogue: Extinction in the Anthropocene -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe live in an age in which we are repeatedly reminded—by scientists, by the media, by popular culture—of the looming threat of mass extinction. We’re told that human activity is currently producing a sixth mass extinction, perhaps of even greater magnitude than the five previous geological catastrophes that drastically altered life on Earth. Indeed, there is a very real concern that the human species may itself be poised to go the way of the dinosaurs, victims of the most recent mass extinction some 65 million years ago. How we interpret the causes, consequences, and moral imperatives of extinction is deeply embedded in the cultural values of any given historical moment. And as David Sepkoski reveals, the history of scientific ideas about extinction over the past two hundred years—as both a past and current process—are implicated in major changes in the way Western society has approached biological and cultural diversity. It seems self-evident to most of us that diverse ecosystems and societies are intrinsically valuable, but the current fascination with diversity is a relatively recent phenomenon. In fact, the way we value diversity depends crucially on our sense that it is precarious—that it is something actively threatened, and that its loss could have profound consequences. In Catastrophic Thinking, Sepkoski uncovers how and why we learned to value diversity as a precious resource at the same time as we learned to think catastrophically about extinction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBiodiversity. 0aExtinction (Biology) 0aExtinction (Biology). 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aDarwin.  aanthropocene.  abiodiversity.  acatastrophes.  aenvironment.  aextinction.  ahistory of science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070480808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020z9783110704600oZDB-23-DPM08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226354613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226354613/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-P